<p><b>Basics</b> <br /></p><p>Neural network is a mathematical function to solve some programming problems which is almost impossible to be solved with conventional programming.</p><p>Neural network consist of neurons and weights. Neurons are made up with activation function and holds output of the function called activation value. Weights are just values which connects one neuron to another. Neurons are grouped and forms a layer. Each layer is connected with other layer by weights. There are three kind of layers; input layer, hidden layer and output layer. Any neural network contains at least one hidden layer, though there might be more than one hidden layers are possible. Input layers accepts input, calculate activation values for next hidden layer, the next layer does same process and pass result to next of it. This goes on until output layer is reached.&nbsp;</p><p>Each layer calculates Z values using weight and activation. Using Z values activation  of next layer is calculated. Once we get activation of output layer we have end result.</p><p>Each layer contains a bias neuron except output layer. The bias neurons always stays at value 1.</p><p>The&nbsp; propagation of activation values from input layer to output layer called forward propagation.</p><p><span style="font-size: x-small;">(Superscript denotes layer index and subscript denotes neuron index. For weights, first digit indicates next layer's neuron index where weight connected to, whereas second digit indicates current layer's neuron index to where weight is connected from two digit subscript) </span></p><p><b><b><img alt="" height="371" src="data:image/png;base64," width="663" /></b>&nbsp;</b></p><p><span style="font-size: x-small;">Figure 1</span><b> <br /></b></p><p><b>Forward propagation</b></p><p>We have two neurons in input layer, three neurons in hidden layer and two in output layer. Each layer except output has one bias neuron.</p><p>Suppose, we have set all weights with proper values and we pass input we will get correct output. The input and activation values should be between 0 to 1 inclusively.<br /></p><p>If we check closely we can see that every neuron from a layer connected to each neuron of next layer using weights. Only bias neuron of next layer stays unaffected from previous layer's values because we want it to stay at 1. We can find out Z value of 1st index neuron of next layer as below.</p><p><img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," />&nbsp;</p><p><span style="font-size: x-small;">Equation 1</span> <br /></p><p>We know that activation of bias is always one and using this we can find out other Z values as below.<br /></p><p><img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p><p><span style="font-size: x-small;">Equations 2 </span><br /></p><p>We will have large positive or negative&nbsp; number as Z values, but we need values between 0 to 1 as activation for next layer. We can have such a function which can give us value between 0 and 0.5 if we pass values between large negative and 0. And if we pass value between 0 and large positive we should get 0.5 to 1 as output. This kind of function is called activation function.</p><p><b>Activation function</b></p><p>There are many types of activation functions, but we will use sigmoid function here as activation function.</p><p><b> </b><img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p><p><b> </b><span style="font-size: x-small;">Equation 3</span> <br /></p><p>The activation function accepts large Z value and returns smaller activation value. So, we need to somehow train the neural network and come up with proper weights. To find out proper weights we going to use "Backward propagation".</p><p><b>Backward propagation</b></p><p>The process starts from output layer and tries to compute weights for each input. We need to iterate the process multiple time to achieve proper weights.</p><p><b> </b><img alt="" height="353" src="data:image/png;base64," width="388" /></p><p><b> </b><span style="font-size: x-small;">Figure 2</span><br /></p><p><b><img alt="" height="353" src="data:image/png;base64," width="387" /> </b></p><p><b> </b><span style="font-size: x-small;">Figure 3</span><br /></p><p>To train the network we need to first initialize all weights with random values. Once we have cost we can figure out how can we minimize the cost and can reach near to correct values.</p><p><b>Cost function</b></p><p><b><b><img alt="" height="36" src="data:image/png;base64," width="370" /></b><br /></b></p><p><span style="font-size: x-small;">Equation 9</span> <br /></p><p>We can describe cost function for each output value as below.</p><p><img alt="" height="87" src="data:image/png;base64," width="409" /></p><p><span style="font-size: x-small;">Equations 10 </span><br /></p><p>Our goal is to minimize the cost. The previous layer's values also dependent on its previous layer (input layer in our example). So, we need to start from output layer and try to find out minimum cost of each neuron going backward up to input layer. This is why the process called backward propagation.</p><p>We need to find <span style="font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; language: en-US; mso-ascii-font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;; mso-fareast-font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;;">?C/?a for each output neuron to find minimum cost. </span><span style="font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; language: en-US; mso-ascii-font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;; mso-fareast-font-family: &quot;Cambria Math&quot;;">?C/?a describes line with 0 slope on curve of function a -&gt; C.
